We sought to identify cases in which replacing (swapping) one of the bacterial blocks (B) for a different block (C) in a reference synthetic community S1 = {A, B}, thereby producing a different synthetic community S2 = {A, C}, would produce a significant increase in shoot Pi content under a certain phosphate condition (pretreatment p phosphate-level q). We can use a trained model to estimate the mean and variance of the plant phenotypic output in every possible synthetic community. The expected Pi content for any input of interest can be calculated as f(xb,p,q,S). The worst-case variance estimate is used in our prediction, in which the largest residual variance (difference between observed value and predicted value) related to a bacterial block is transferred from the training data to all related conditions. Specifically,




